member.example:
Let your forms inherit from  instead of inheriting
. For example, when you have a form
MyForm:

using System.Windows.Forms;

namespace Sample
{
  public partial class MyForm : Form
  {
    ...
  }
}

Just changes the lines to:

using System.Windows.Forms;
using DigitalRune.Windows.Docking;

namespace Sample
{
  public partial class MyForm : DockableForm
  {
    ...
  }
}

This will add docking capabilities to your form. When you open the modified
form in Visual Studio (design-mode), you will be able to see new properties 
in the Properties dialog. The docking properties can be found 
in the category named 'Docking'.

remarks.para:
            There are two ways to make your forms dockable:
            


            
            The Fast Way: Let your forms inherit from  instead of inheriting
            . For example, when you have a form
            MyForm:
            
            using System.Windows.Forms;
            
            namespace Sample
            {
              public partial class MyForm : Form
              {
                ...
              }
            }
            
            Just changes the lines to:
            
            using System.Windows.Forms;
            using DigitalRune.Windows.Docking;
            
            namespace Sample
            {
              public partial class MyForm : DockableForm
              {
                ...
              }
            }
            
            This will add docking capabilities to your form. When you open the modified
            form in Visual Studio (design-mode), you will be able to see new properties 
            in the Properties dialog. The docking properties can be found 
            in the category named 'Docking'.
            
            


            
            The Slow Way: Implement the interface  
            in your own forms. This takes more code to write, but gives you full control
            over the docking in your form.

member.remarks:
If the  property is set, the form
will be displayed as  docking state;
otherwise it will be displayed as a normal form.
